==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: mnage trois
<hw>m⟦eacute⟧`nage ⟦agrave⟧` trois"</hw> <pr>(m⟦asl⟧`n⟦adot⟧zh"
⟦adot⟧ trw⟦adot⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., household for
three]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A relationship involving three people,
especially one in which three people live together and have sexual
relations, such as a married couple and a lover of one of the
pair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A single sexual encounter in which three people
participate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <mark>[figurative]</mark> <def>An unlikely situation in
which a group of three people not normally associated with each other
participate in an activity together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q> For the first time in World Championships history, two racers
shared the first-place gold medal. <persfn>Maier</persfn> and
<persfn>Kjus</persfn> arm-in-arm on the podium, with Austrian
<person>Hans Knauss</person> just .01 seconds back from making it a
<qex>menage-a-trois</qex>.</q>⟦br⟧
<qau>Andrew Hood
(http://classic.mountainzone.com/ski/worldcup/99/worldchamps/superg-m.html)</qau>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menagerie</ent>⟦br⟧
